[2]
Date: Tue 10 Aug 2010
Source: Saskatoon Homepage [edited]
<http://www.saskatoonhomepage.ca/index.php?option=com_content&id=26783&task=view>


Anthrax case in Saskatchewan
----------------------------
No area in the province should consider itself immune to an anthrax
scenario. The province has recorded its 1st case for 2010. It's in the RM
[rural municipality] of Wellington south east of Regina near Weyburn. And
it's affecting a bison herd. About half the 90 head herd has died so far.

The chief veterinary officer with Saskatchewan Agriculture, Dr Greg
Douglas, says with the amount of water and flooding that we had this spring
[2010] it's plausible that many of the pastures that didn't previously have
any problems could now be contaminated. Douglas says all producers in the
province should consider vaccinating their animals for anthrax and no area
of the province should consider itself immune. Having said that, there are
higher risk areas. Those are areas where there was substantial flooding,
those that have had anthrax cases within the past 5 years, and those where
the soil is alkaline or basic.

Vaccination is the best method of protection for cattle, sheep, goats, and
horses. The vaccine requires 7 to 10 days for immunity to develop and will
provide protection for 6 to 12 months.

Douglas says watching for signs of the disease before deciding whether or
not to vaccinate is not the way to go because anthrax really is a sudden
death in a herd. He says everything can look fine and the signs of disease
are so quick producers won't have the opportunity to act. The animal can go
from being seemingly completely fine to being dead in 2 hours time.

Saskatchewan had a serious anthrax problem in 2006; 804 livestock deaths
were reported, mainly in north east, north central, and east central
regions. These included 493 cattle, 253 bison, 33 sheep, 13 deer and elk,
as well as 6 horses.

