[3]
Date: Tue 10 Aug 2010
From: Kim Knight-Picketts <kim.knight-picketts@inspection.gc.ca> [edited]


"The 1st case of anthrax in Saskatchewan for 2010 has occurred in the
southern part of the province. The infected herd is a bison herd consisting
of 500 animals, 100 of which are on a separate pasture where approximately
30 have died. The deaths include 100 per cent of the bulls, and about 30
per cent of the females.

The carcass-side screening test kit was used by the CFIA [Canadian Food
Inspection Agency] district vet, following a postmortem by a private
veterinarian on 1 Aug 2010, after the producer reported 10 deaths. Given
negative results to the screening test, other reasons for deaths were
explored. Blue green algae were ruled out.

A 2nd private veterinarian examined the herd and performed a postmortem on
3 Aug 2010, as death losses continued. The only finding was an enlarged
spleen, consistent with anthrax, but preliminary smears at a private lab
were inconclusive. Anthrax was confirmed by the CFIA lab on 6 Aug 2010, on
samples collected from the 1st animal tested on 1 Aug 2010. Culture results
at the private lab on the 3 Aug 2010 sample were also considered highly
suspicious of anthrax, and were forwarded to the CFIA lab on 5 Aug 2010
with anthrax confirmation on 6 Aug 2010.

CFIA tested 2 more dead animals on 4 Aug 2010, as deaths continued. These 2
animals had a negative result and a weak positive result with the
carcass-side test, which were confirmed by CFIA lab results of one negative
and one positive on anthrax culture.

Deaths, including calves, continued throughout this past weekend [7-8 Aug
2010] (exact numbers being confirmed). Antibiotics had been started and
therefore vaccination will be delayed, but will proceed once antibiotic
treatments cease. All carcasses have been, or are being buried, with C&D
[control and disinfection] efforts continuing.

An update will be provided as information becomes available.

Comment: The false negative results of the pen-side screening test may have
delayed confirmation of this infection. Continued testing was required to
confirm anthrax in this herd. Postmortems may be necessary in such cases,
and must be done with care to reduce contamination. Questions are being
posed regarding the sensitivity of this screening test for use in bison.

The location of the infected site is provided at
<http://www.inspection.gc.ca/english/anima/disemala/anthchar/situatione.shtml>.

--
Dr Kim Knight-Picketts BSc(Agr), DVM
A/Senior Staff Veterinarian
Disease Control, Canadian Food Inspection Agency
Charlottetown, PE
Canada
<kim.knight-picketts@inspection.gc.ca>

[This outbreak is very similar to that on the Flying-D ranch in Montana,
USA, in 2008. The 1st thing to do in these circumstances is to get the herd
out of the pasture, and get them treated and vaccinated. The 100 per cent
death rate among bison bulls is not unusual, but costly.

How the rains played a part is probably 2-fold:
1. providing a good hatch of horse flies to spread the infection through
the herd, and
2. it probably floated up the spores in the various (?bison) graves from
previous cases on this or other nearby ranches.

Cattle and bison are large creatures and therefore any grave of these
animals will collapse inwards as the carcasses decompose to produce a
modest basin. This/these will collect rain, provide extra grazing, and move
any spores to the surface where they can be acquired by animals grazing the
site.

Why the US Navy test kits were not up to their expected efficiency is
unclear at this time. The usual reason for false negatives are
inappropriate species (white tail deer always come up negative) but we have
had consistent good success with plains bison and wood bison elsewhere. The
other regular problem is when the carcasses are tested after too long an
interval after death. With cattle, tests will go negative around the 3rd
day as decomposition will reduce the titre of protective antigen below the
test threshold for positivity. A preliminary answer from my CFIA colleagues
indicates that they believe that one of these false negative carcasses was
"fresh" as was the weak positive. CFIA obtains fresh test kits each year
for distribution. - Mod.MHJ

The province of Saskatchewan can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map of Canada at <http://healthmap.org/r/02lr>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
